{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048170,"nonce":"boFueof1MUKKlS2jsCIUAy9n32k=","title":"Add Penzai-like selector API for interpretability research","message":"[Imported from GitHub #38] (created 2026-01-26T15:55:56Z)\n\n## Motivation\n\nAs Feedbax matures toward supporting interpretability and mechanistic analysis of trained models, we need ergonomic tools for surgical model manipulation—selecting specific components, patching activations, ablating circuits, and inspecting intermediate states.\n\nPenzai's selector system (`pz.select`) provides a compelling API for this: fluent method chaining over PyTree selections with operations like `.at_instances_of()`, `.where()`, `.apply()`, and `.partition()`. However, adopting Penzai wholesale would require abandoning our Equinox-based architecture.\n\n## Proposal\n\nImplement a lightweight selector system (~250-400 lines) inspired by Penzai but native to Equinox/Feedbax. This would complement existing utilities in `_tree.py` and `eqx.tree_at`.\n\n### Core features (minimal viable)\n\n- `Selection` class holding `selected_by_path: dict[KeyPath, PyTree]` and `remainder: PyTree`\n- Boundary-marking algorithm for multi-node selection\n- `.apply(fn)` / `.set(value)` - transform selected subtrees\n- `.at_instances_of(type)` - type-based selection\n- `.where(predicate)` - filter current selection\n- `.deselect()` - reconstruct original tree\n\n### Extended features (as needed)\n\n- `.partition()` / `.invert()` - split tree into selected/unselected\n- `.at_children()`, `.at_pytree_leaves()` - traversal patterns\n- `.get_by_path()` / `.set_by_path()` - keypath-indexed operations\n- Integration with `Graph` surgery API\n\n## Use cases\n\n1. **Activation patching**: Select all `StateIndex` nodes of a particular type, replace with cached values\n2. **Ablation studies**: Zero out specific network layers or channels\n3. **Gradient masking**: Partition parameters for selective training\n4. **Circuit analysis**: Extract and inspect subgraphs by component type\n\n## Complexity estimate\n\nBased on analysis of Penzai's `selectors.py` (~650 lines of code):\n- Core mechanism: ~150-200 lines\n- Convenience traversals: ~150-200 lines  \n- We already have: `eqx.tree_at`, `eqx.partition`, `tree_labels`, keypath utilities\n\nA useful implementation could be achieved in 250-400 lines.\n\n## References\n\n- [Penzai selectors documentation](https://penzai.readthedocs.io/en/stable/notebooks/selectors.html)\n- [Penzai source](https://github.com/google-deepmind/penzai/blob/main/penzai/core/selectors.py)\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}